## Deployment Safety Review for Plan [PLAN_NUMBER]

### Phase 1: Deployment Strategy

**Q1.1: Strategy classification**

| Aspect | Value | Rationale |
|--------|-------|-----------|
| Strategy type | Blue-green / Canary / Rolling / Recreate | |
| Traffic shift | Instant / Gradual / Manual | |
| Rollback mechanism | Automatic / Manual / Both | |
| Deployment window | Business hours / Maintenance window / 24/7 | |

- [ ] Strategy matches risk profile (high-risk changes use canary or blue-green)
- [ ] Traffic shift is controllable and reversible
- [ ] Rollback does not require code changes (config or traffic shift only)

**Q1.2: Blast radius**

| Change Type | Affected Users/Services | Mitigation |
|-------------|-------------------------|------------|
| Application deploy | | |
| Config change | | |
| Database migration | | |
| Infrastructure change | | |

- [ ] Blast radius is bounded (canary percentage, single region, feature flags)
- [ ] Worst-case failure scenario is documented
- [ ] Rollback time objective (RTO) is defined

---

### Phase 2: Health Checks and Readiness

**Q2.1: Health check design**

| Check Type | Endpoint/Probe | Success Criteria | Failure Action |
|------------|----------------|------------------|----------------|
| Liveness | | | Restart container |
| Readiness | | | Remove from LB |
| Startup | | | Delay traffic |

- [ ] Liveness detects hung processes (not just HTTP 200)
- [ ] Readiness excludes instance from load until fully initialized
- [ ] Startup probe prevents premature kill during slow boot
- [ ] Health checks do not depend on external services that may be down

**Q2.2: Dependency health**

- [ ] Database connectivity verified before accepting traffic
- [ ] Cache/queue connectivity verified or gracefully degraded
- [ ] External API dependencies have circuit breakers or fallbacks
- [ ] Health check failure triggers rollback or traffic shift

---

### Phase 3: Rollback Triggers

**Q3.1: Automatic rollback conditions**

| Condition | Threshold | Action | Verified? |
|-----------|------------|--------|-----------|
| Error rate | | Rollback / Pause | |
| Latency P99 | | Rollback / Pause | |
| Crash loop | | Rollback | |
| Health check failure | | Rollback | |
| Custom metric | | | |

- [ ] Automatic rollback triggers are defined and tested
- [ ] Thresholds are tuned (not too sensitive, not too slow)
- [ ] Rollback does not cascade (e.g., rollback of rollback)
- [ ] Manual override exists for false positives

**Q3.2: Manual rollback procedure**

- [ ] Runbook documents step-by-step rollback
- [ ] Rollback can be executed by on-call without code access
- [ ] Rollback time is measured and meets RTO
- [ ] Post-rollback verification steps exist
- [ ] Rollback is rehearsed (drill or staging)

---

### Phase 4: Circuit Breakers and Degradation

**Q4.1: Circuit breaker configuration**

| Dependency | Circuit State | Open Threshold | Half-Open Test |
|------------|---------------|----------------|----------------|
| | Closed / Open / Half-Open | | |

- [ ] External dependencies have circuit breakers
- [ ] Open circuit fails fast (no long timeouts)
- [ ] Half-open allows recovery testing
- [ ] Fallback behavior is defined (cached response, error message, degraded mode)

**Q4.2: Graceful degradation**

- [ ] Non-critical features can be disabled without full outage
- [ ] Feature flags support instant disable
- [ ] Degradation path is tested in staging

---

### Phase 5: Deployment Checklist

**Q5.1: Pre-deployment**

- [ ] Change is peer reviewed
- [ ] Rollback plan is documented and approved
- [ ] Database migrations are backward compatible (or have rollback script)
- [ ] Feature flags or kill switches are in place for risky changes
- [ ] On-call is aware of deployment window
- [ ] Monitoring dashboards are open and alerts are acknowledged

**Q5.2: During deployment**

- [ ] Deployment is incremental (canary percentage, region)
- [ ] Metrics are monitored during traffic shift
- [ ] Rollback decision point is defined (e.g., after 5 min, after 1% traffic)
- [ ] Communication channel is active (Slack, PagerDuty)

**Q5.3: Post-deployment**

- [ ] Verification steps completed (smoke tests, spot checks)
- [ ] Error rate and latency compared to pre-deployment baseline
- [ ] Rollback procedure validated (even if not needed)
- [ ] Runbook updated if procedure changed

---

### Phase 6: Data Migration Safety

**Q6.1: Migration strategy**

| Migration Type | Strategy | Rollback | Verified? |
|----------------|----------|----------|-----------|
| Schema change | | | |
| Data backfill | | | |
| Feature flag cutover | | | |

- [ ] Migrations are backward compatible (additive) where possible
- [ ] Destructive migrations have rollback scripts
- [ ] Data migration can be reverted without data loss
- [ ] Migration is tested on production-like data volume in staging

